To fix the vulnerability in the provided code snippet and prevent Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks, you need to properly escape and sanitize the user input before outputting it to the response. One common approach to prevent XSS is to use libraries that provide output encoding functions.

Here's an updated version of the code with proper security measures implemented using OWASP's ESAPI library for Java:

```java
import java.io.*;
import javax.servlet.*;
import javax.servlet.http.*;

import org.owasp.esapi.ESAPI;
import org.owasp.esapi.codecs.HTMLEntityCodec;

public class SecureServlet extends HttpServlet {
    protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) throws ServletException, IOException {
        String userInput = request.getParameter("input");

        // Encode user input using ESAPI HTML entity encoding
        HTMLEntityCodec codec = new HTMLEntityCodec();
        String encodedInput = codec.encodeForHTML(userInput);

        // Output sanitized user input
        PrintWriter out = response.getWriter();
        out.println("<html>");
        out.println("<body>");
        out.println("<h1>User Input:</h1>");
        out.println(encodedInput);
        out.println("</body>");
        out.println("</html>");
    }
}

